SIMPLE: temporality
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Temporality
<hw>Tem`po*ral"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Temporalities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>temporalitas</ets>, in LL., possessions of the church: cf. F.
<ets>temporalit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or
quality of being temporary; -- opposed to
<xex>perpetuity</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The laity; temporality.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir T. More.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which pertains to temporal welfare; material
interests; especially, the revenue of an ecclesiastic proceeding from
lands, tenements, or lay fees, tithes, and the like; -- chiefly used in
the plural.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Supreme head, . . . under God, of the spirituality and
<qex>temporality</qex> of the same church.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Temporally</ent>⟦br⟧
